profile_positions.description:
The European Laboratory for Intelligent and Learning Systems (ELLIS) Unit in Amsterdam is a local branch of the ELLIS Society, a diverse European network that promotes research excellence and advances breakthroughs in Artificial Intelligence (AI). Beyond acting as the local touchpoint for the ELLIS Society, ELLIS Amsterdam brings together top talent from local stakeholders to provide opportunities for students, faculty, researchers, and industry, conduct fundamental basic research, and develop infrastructure for excellence in machine learning in the Netherlands and throughout Europe.

I perform the following duties: 
•  Manage the ELLIS Amsterdam Unit ecosystem; 
• Serve as the first point of contact for the ELLIS Amsterdam unit; 
• Maintain partnerships; 
• Manage local and national initiatives /projects and ensure its timely implementation;
• Support the ELLIS Amsterdam unit in its community-building;
• Stay up-to-date with ELLIS processes, developments, and events.

I performed the following roles, as follows: 
- Assisted in the designing, implementing, and evaluating of regional policies and agreements between ASEAN and its European partners, through researches and analyses;
- Monitored and reported progress of multi-sector cooperation between ASEAN and its European partners through progress reports, briefing notes, presentations, and speeches;
- Effectively managed a portfolio of regional projects and programs amounting funded by European partners by providing strategic and administrative supports, including budgeting, compliance to funding requirements and solving of complex issues.

The Association of Southeast Asian Nations, or ASEAN, was established on 8 August 1967 in Bangkok, Thailand, with the signing of the ASEAN Declaration (Bangkok Declaration) by the Founding Fathers of ASEAN, namely Indonesia, Malaysia, Philippines, Singapore and Thailand. Brunei Darussalam then joined on 7 January 1984, Viet Nam on 28 July 1995, Lao PDR and Myanmar on 23 July 1997, and Cambodia on 30 April 1999, making up what is today the ten Member States of ASEAN.

My primary roles at Tusk Advisory are: 
- Ensured timely implementation of Indonesia’s national priority One Map Policy (OMP), through Project Management Office (PMO) support, including stakeholders management and development of communication strategy and materials;
- Provided support to research in facilitation of conflict resolution and enhancement of the national geospatial network (JIGN) of National Geospatial Agency (BIG);           
- Supported the designing of an implementation model for the Indonesia Illumination Program (PIT) focusing on renewable energy to the Ministry of Energy and Mineral Resources (KESDM);
- Conducted PMO support of the PIT, including a regulatory analysis and finalization of communication materials; 
- Assisted in-depth research and analysis, as well as facilitated strategic discussions with relevant stakeholders, which resulted in a comprehensive solar panel industry development strategy in Indonesia to the Coordinating Ministry of Maritime Affairs (CMMA).

Tusk Advisory Private Limited is a strategic advisory firm focused on delivering infrastructure projects in the Asia Pacific region with a significant presence in Indonesia, via its subsidiary PT Tusk Advisory. Tusk has an impressive track record in assisting governments transact PPP projects, developing infrastructure and economic growth strategies as well as designing and establishing brand new institutions for infrastructure delivery - including infrastructure financing institutions, infrastructure regulators and infrastructure coordination agencies.  

On the private sector side, Tusk has acted as transaction or bid managers for large infrastructure projects, developed and executed infrastructure investment strategies as well managed infrastructure centric M&As in both Sell-Side and Buy-Side via its subsidiary Tusk Capital Partners.

My main responsibilities at AIIA are, as follows: 
- Facilitated coordination between AIIA and relevant stakeholders, such as the Asian Development Bank (ADB), Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade (DFAT) of Australia, and Australia National University (ANU) pertaining to ongoing projects, such as workshops and conferences;
- Developed communication materials in regard to the AIIA's participation in Global Think Tank Summit 2015; 
- Provided support in the preparation and publication of the AIIA events, such as the Australia-Indonesia Dialogue;
- Provided a day-to-day support to the operational activities of the AIIA.

The Australian Institute of International Affairs (AIIA) is an independent, non-profit organisation promoting interest in and understanding of international affairs in Australia. It provides a forum for discussion and debate, but does not seek to formulate its own institutional views. The institute arranges programs of lectures, seminars, workshops, conferences and other discussions, and sponsors research and publications. The AIIA was formed in 1924 and established as a federal body in 1933 and is the only nationwide organisation of its kind in Australia. It is financed by members’ contributions, a small government subvention and tax deductible donations from individuals and businesses.

AIIA is voted the top think tank in Southeast Asia and the Pacific in the Global Go To Think Tanks Index in 2015, 2016 and 2017.

